snippet.textDisplay: I’m an American citizen currently living and working in Beijing, China. The government here has canceled school and closed businesses for an additional week after the Chinese New Year, CNY. One of the biggest reasons for the panic is/was that this is the time of year the entire country is on vacation and traveling all over China. And once the CNY is over people will be traveling back to their towns. Making it easier to spread since most cities have a large number of people. Beijing in particular has over 21 million people. All in all, most people here aren’t panicking. As long as you use Personal protective equipment,PPE, and common sense you’re fine. That doesn’t mean that the disease has stopped spreading because Dr. Mike is right. Since they don’t know if you can catch it while your not showing symptoms that makes it harder to contain. The deaths so far have been people with underlying health conditions and or the elderly.

snippet.textDisplay:
As of today the US Infected numbers are holding at 11.  However we have heard nothing as to why none of them have been moved over to the Recovered Category.  Are we to believe the first individual infected in the US who showed symptoms on Jan. 16th is still hospitalized?  This morning a paper out of Taiwan is reporting on what may have been an accidental leak on the "Epidemic Situation Tracker" of the true Infection and Death numbers within China putting the mortality rate at 15.9% as of Feb. 2nd. 

We need more information from world governments.  More accurate information now would allow populations to take actions necessary to head off spreads.  I don't care if it involves roadblocks and checkpoints when the time comes.  Political and economic ramifications be damned. 

New England Journal of Medicine - First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States

snippet.textDisplay:
Plague Journal


Day 1


Am starting this just in case I actually do come down with Corona-chan. The old lady who does the morning checkout coughed while racking up my groceries. Might just be my paranoia, but it can’t hurt to start a journal to track symptoms if they do appear. My schedule is pretty off-hours, so I likely won’t infect too many people if I’m carrying it already.

On the walk home from the grocery store, I felt out of breath. I know that’s one of the symptoms, but I highly doubt the virus works that fast, and it’s not unusual for me to feel out of breath carrying the groceries home. Will try to remember to record every day, even if there’s nothing unusual that happens.

I have enough food and water to last 10 days from now, and if I ration my food it might last that long. Will try to eat less, especially junk. Can’t take the risk of sabotaging my immune system. Will also try to minimize contact with the outside world except for work and getting food/water. I think I’ll use the nearby Walmart, since they have autocashiers. If I just stay away from other customers and employees I could limit the chances of future exposure and/or infectivity.

Wish me luck anons!
